{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15545"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15545"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.39,0.13,0.04,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"},{"type":"tags","id":"10130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of thyroid dysfunction on serum glucose levels?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperthyroidism causes decreased serum glucose","Hyperthyroidism causes increased serum glucose","Hypothyroidism causes increased serum glucose","Hypothyroidism causes decreased serum glucose","Thyroid dysfunction has no effect on serum glucose"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates the important relationship between thyroid function and glucose metabolism. \u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism causes increased serum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E through several mechanisms. Excess thyroid hormone increases hepatic gluconeogenesis, accelerates gastrointestinal glucose absorption, and enhances insulin degradation. These effects can worsen glycaemic control in patients with diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism causing decreased serum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While thyroid hormone does increase glucose utilisation in peripheral tissues, the net effect is hyperglycaemia due to increased glucose production and turnover.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism causing increased serum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Hypothyroidism actually tends to improve glycaemic control in diabetic patients due to reduced hepatic glucose output and decreased insulin degradation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism causing decreased serum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E can occur due to reduced hepatic glucose production and decreased intestinal glucose absorption, though the effect is usually mild in non-diabetic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid dysfunction having no effect on serum glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Thyroid hormones play a crucial role in regulating glucose metabolism through multiple pathways including effects on insulin secretion, glucose absorption, and hepatic glucose production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe relationship between thyroid and glucose metabolism is clinically significant. Changes in thyroid function can affect diabetes control, and new onset thyroid dysfunction should be considered in diabetic patients with unexplained changes in glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperthyroidism increases glucose metabolism and can worsen glycaemic control in diabetic patients.","Hypothyroidism decreases glucose metabolism and can improve glycaemic control in diabetic patients.","Both hyper- and hypothyroidism can affect insulin sensitivity and glucose homeostasis."],"references":["Eom YS, Wilson JR, Bernet VJ. Links between Thyroid Disorders and Glucose Homeostasis. Diabetes Metab J. 2022 Mar;46(2):239-256. doi: 10.4093/dmj.2022.0013. Epub 2022 Mar 24. PMID: 35385635; PMCID: PMC8987680.","Jahagirdar V, McNay EC. Thyroid hormone\u0027s role in regulating brain glucose metabolism and potentially modulating hippocampal cognitive processes. Metab Brain Dis. 2012 Jun;27(2):101-11. doi: 10.1007/s11011-012-9291-0. Epub 2012 Mar 23. PMID: 22437199; PMCID: PMC3348399.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T13:44:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T13:44:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoj